               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t17800628-117-off588-c1282" targOrder="Y" targets="t17800628-117-defend1541 t17800628-117-off588 t17800628-117-verdict587"></join>
         
               <p>424. 
               
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-defend1541" type="defendantName">
                     LUKE 
                     HAND
                  <interp inst="t17800628-117-defend1541" type="surname" value="HAND"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-defend1541" type="given" value="LUKE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-defend1541" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t17800628-117-off584" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-off584" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-off584" type="offenceSubcategory" value="riot"></interp>
               that he, together with forty other persons and more, did, unlawfully, riotously, and tumultuously, assemble, on the <rs id="t17800628-117-cd585" type="crimeDate">7th of June</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17800628-117-off584 t17800628-117-cd585"></join>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17800628-117-off588 t17800628-117-cd585"></join>, to the disturbance of the public peace, and did begin to demolish and pull down the dwelling house of 
                     
                        <persName id="t17800628-117-victim1543" type="victimName">
                           William 
                           Gerrard
                        <interp inst="t17800628-117-victim1543" type="surname" value="Gerrard"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t17800628-117-victim1543" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t17800628-117-victim1543" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , against the form of the statute, &amp;c.
            </rs>
               </p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1544">
                  ELIZABETH
                   COUCH
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1544" type="surname" value="COUCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1544" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1544" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>My husband keeps horses and carts to let out; we live in Pear-Tree-street, in the Parish of <placeName id="t17800628-117-crimeloc586">St. Luke's</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17800628-117-crimeloc586" type="placeName" value="St. Luke's"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17800628-117-crimeloc586" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17800628-117-off584 t17800628-117-crimeloc586"></join>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17800628-117-off588 t17800628-117-crimeloc586"></join>, almost opposite to Mr. Gerrard's. Upon the 7th of June, between ten and eleven o'clock, the mob came by our door; the first person I saw was the prisoner and a man in blue drummer's clothes; the prisoner had an ax over his left shoulder; the mob got very thick to Mr. Gerrard's door. Then the prisoner called shew a book, and a bible was put out; presently after I saw two pannels of the door broke with the thick part of the ax, I believe; I did not see him break any other part of the house; then the mob got in, and the first man I saw at the one-pair-of-stairs window was the prisoner at the bar; he leaned out of the window, waved his hand, and said buzza! all Popery! A very little after that I saw him bring a drawer of linen and books to the window, and he cried again buzza, all Popery. Our house is opposite; our yard adjoins Mr. Gerrard's house; they wanted to burn the things in our yard. I desired they would not, as there were wooden things in the yard. The furniture was thrown out at the windows, the windows were broke, and the wainscoting torn sadly by the side of the windows; and two of the middle pannels were broke. The prisoner, I believe, continued there three quarters of an hour; I did not see him come out but I saw him go down the street with something to burn, but what it was I do not know.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178006280271"></xptr>Cross Examination.</p>
               <p>How long had you known the prisoner before? - I never saw him before; I knew him because he was so tall.</p>
               <p>When did you see him again? - The Monday after in New Prison. My husband said I should go to see if it was the same person I had given a description of him before to my husband, and one Mr. Hawei, that he was a very tall man, and had some defect in his mouth.</p>
               <p>Are you sure it was an ax, was it not a bag of tools? - No, it was not a bag of tools, I believe it was an ax.</p>
               <p>What sort of hat had he on? - I did not take notice of his hat. I am sure he is the man whom I saw the night of the riot.</p>
               <p>Court. What sort of coat had he on that night? - A lightish loose coat.</p>
               <p>How came you to take such particular notice of his mouth? - I thought he looked odd with it.</p>
               <p>Counsel. Did you see the defect as he went along or when he spoke? - I did not hear him speak.</p>
               <p>Can you see a defect of his mouth as you stand there? - Yes, any body may see it if they look at him.</p>
               <p>Court. Upon your oath did you not first perceive that defect in his mouth when you saw him in the prison? - No, I saw it first as he came up the street.</p>
               <p>When the prisoner came to the window he spoke? - Yes, he cried huzza, all Popery. I did not hear him speak in the street.</p>
               <p>Upon your oath is the prisoner the man you saw in Gerrard's house? - Upon my oath I think he is; I know he is.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1545">
                  ALICE
                   BRIDGES
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1545" type="surname" value="BRIDGES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1545" type="given" value="ALICE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1545" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I live in Peartree-street. On Wednesday evening, when the mob came there I was standing at my door. The prisoner was the first man I saw; there were a great number of people with him hallooing all up the street; I did not hear what they said; I afterwards saw the prisoner at Mr. Gerrard's one-pair-of-stairs window; he put his hand upon the ledge, and cried out huzza, all popery by G - d. I saw him break the glass of the beauset, and pull the wainscoting out of the window and throw it into the street; he then went to the next window and took the top drawer out of a chest of drawers which was full of linen; and he brought it upon his head to the window, and threw it out and huzza'd; he then threw out a quart bowl full of some thing, and huzza'd. I did not see him afterwards; I am perfectly sure the prisoner is the man; it was near eleven o'clock at night when I saw him; I went afterwards with Mr. Crouch to the prison, and saw him, and I knew him directly by a disfigurement I observed in his teeth.</p>
               <p>Was you very near him when you observed that? - Yes, the window was not very high; I was opposite, not above seven or eight yards off. He had a light great coat on quite open, a leathern apron, and he had an ax in his hand. I staid there about ten minutes.</p>
               <p>Court. How long was you with this man in the prison? - Not long; he was in the yard; I had no conversation with him; he was talking to a number of persons in the prison.</p>
               <p>Upon your oath was not the time you saw him in the prison the first time you observed the defect in his teeth? - No, I observed it when I saw him at the window.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1546">
                  THOMAS
                   MAYES
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1546" type="surname" value="MAYES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1546" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1546" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a tailor and salesman; I live in Golden-lane. I have known the prisoner four or five years, or more.</p>
               <p>Was you in company with him on Thursday the 8th of June? - Wednesday or Thursday, I do not know which, I was at the Crown Alehouse with him in the morning, at about eleven or twelve o'clock, in company with 
               <persName id="t17800628-117-person1547">
                  John
                   Bradoury
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1547" type="surname" value="Bradoury"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1547" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1547" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , the landlord of the house, and two other persons, 
               <persName id="t17800628-117-person1548">
                  John
                   Lynch
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1548" type="surname" value="Lynch"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1548" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1548" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and a Mr. Barton, a carpenter; there were several others, whom I cannot name. It was I believe the morning after the fire at Mr. Lynch's. The prisoner said he was at the pulling down of all the houses in London and burning them at the fires. I saw him at Lynch's the night before, but did not see him do any thing.</p>
               <p>Cross Examination.</p>
               <p>Do you know the prisoner? - Yes, very well.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178006280272"></xptr>Was he drunk at that time? - No, I do not think he was.</p>
               <p>Then he must be mad? - I do not think he is a madman; I think he is a man who knows things very well.</p>
               <p>He said he was at the pulling down and burning all the houses in London, how came that to be the subject of conversation? - I cannot say; I heard him say only that.</p>
               <p>You saw him at Lynch's doing nothing at all? - Yes.</p>
               <p>Counsel for the prisoner. Then you could have contradicted him as to that fact at least.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1549">
                  JOHN
                   BRADBURY
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1549" type="surname" value="BRADBURY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1549" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1549" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I keep a publick-house in Golden-lane. The prisoner was at my house on Thursday, Friday, or Saturday. I do not know which, but it was after Mr. Lynch's and my house were demolished. He said, he had been at all the fires in London. That was all I heard him say; He did not say it to me, he said it to other people.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1550">
                  JOHN
                   LYNCH
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1550" type="surname" value="LYNCH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1550" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1550" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I was in company with the prisoner at Mr. Bradbury's two or three days after my house was demolished. I did not remark the day. Mayes, the prisoner, and some others were drinking. Mayes and he had some words. The prisoner said he had been at all the fires, and all the houses which had been done. I looked very earnestly at him, but did not recollect seeing him at my house. He said, he had been at all the fires, and pulling down the houses in London. Those were the words as near as I can recollect.</p>
               <p>Can you recollect how long this conversation was after the demolishing of your house? - It was the same week. My house was pulled down on the Tuesday; I am sure it was not the Wednesday.</p>
               <p>Did he speak as if he had been active in it? - He did not say he had been doing it; he might be a spectator.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1551">
                  EDWARD
                   BEVAN
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1551" type="surname" value="BEVAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1551" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1551" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>The prisoner came to my house on the 7th of June, about midnight with the mob, he came into the house and said to the mob, there was no Popery there, the house should not come down. He seemed to have the conduct of the mob. I never saw him before. He was brought to me when he was taken, and I said I could swear to him; I am sure he is the man.</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>I do not want to make a long and tedious defence. I am innocent of the things laid to my charge. I hope this court will not convict the innocent by the evidence of persons of notorious bad morals.</p>
               <p>For the Prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1552">
                  RICHARD
                   REYNOLDS
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1552" type="surname" value="REYNOLDS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1552" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1552" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>The prisoner is a carpenter and joiner; he was at work at Mr. Scott's, on Holbourn-hill, on the 7th of June, with me, from one o'clock till between six and seven when we parted, but where he went I cannot say.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1553">
                  MARY
                   KEMP
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1553" type="surname" value="KEMP"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1553" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1553" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I live in Crown-court, Golden-lane. The prisoner lodges next door to me. He was at my house on the 7th of June, to the best of my remembrance it was at near eight o'clock. He staid about half an hour, and by the desire of the neighbours he chalked, No Popery on all the shutters in the court. The neighbours said Mr. Murphy's, the sign of the Sun was pulled down. He said, it was sad work.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1554">
                  ANN
                   HAYWARD
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1554" type="surname" value="HAYWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1554" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1554" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am daughter to the last witness; I live at No. 14, Crown-court. The prisoner has lodged with me two years. On the 7th of June he came home about half after seven o'clock, with his tools on his back; he staid about half an hour; then he went out and returned about twelve o'clock.</p>
               <p>Was he drunk? - No, I never saw him drunk, he is a very sober man.</p>
               <p>Cross Examination.</p>
               <p>Was you gone to bed when he came home? - I cannot recollect whether I was or no. My husband was gone to Mr. Langdale's at Holbourn. My husband generally fits up to let him in; I believe I was in bed; I cannot be sure whether I saw him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1555">
                  JAMES
                   HAYWARD
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1555" type="surname" value="HAYWARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1555" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1555" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>The prisoner has lodged with me between two and three years. On the 7th of June, between ten and eleven o'clock at night, I met him with one 
               <persName id="t17800628-117-person1556">
                  Martin
                   Harrison
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1556" type="surname" value="Harrison"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1556" type="given" value="Martin"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1556" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , on<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178006280273"></xptr> Snow-hill, coming towards home; I tapped him on the shoulder, and asked him where he was going; he said, home; we stopped about ten minutes at the end of Fleet-market to look at Mr. Langdale's house, which was then on fire, and then came home together. He and Harrison then went out to get a bit of supper; I let them both in between twelve and one o'clock; they lodged at my house. The prisoner is an honest industrious man, never accustomed to stay out late.</p>
               <p>Cross Examination.</p>
               <p>Was your wife up when you came home? - Yes, and let us in.</p>
               <p>Who generally sits up for the prisoner? - He never stays out late, except by chance, then he lets us know.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1557">
                  MARTIN
                   HARRISON
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1557" type="surname" value="HARRISON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1557" type="given" value="MARTIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1557" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I live at No. 74, in Fore street; on Tuesday the 6th of June, the prisoner and I went to Peckham, we supped there at eleven o'clock; then I came home to his lodging, and slept with him that night; I got up in the morning and went to work; about a quarter after seven in the evening on Wednesday, I met him with a bag of tools on his back, he asked me to go home and have a bit of supper with him; when we came to the end of the court, in sight of Murphy's hous e, Murphy's house was very near down, it was between seven and eight o'clock; he made use of an oath and said, Who would have thought they would have pulled his house down! he shook his head and said, Bad work! bad work! we went up the court to his lodging; Mrs. Hayward was quite frightened, and said,</p>
               <p>"Mr. Hand, they will certainly come up this court," and she got him to write No Popery on the window-shutters; we staid near half an hour, and then went out to the end of the court; they said the mob were going to pull down Mr. Cassaday's house, which is higher up; we went to Mr. Cassaday's; Mr. Hand said, he hoped they would not pull the house down, he would try to pacify them. The mob came round there twice; they gave the mob beer, and pacified them; we staid to supper, and went home to his lodging a little before twelve; St. Paul's struck remarkably loud as we went down the lane; I observed to him, that St. Paul's struck remarkably loud; he replied, there will be rain. Then we went to his lodging; we saw Mr. Hayward, I believe Mrs. Hayward was in bed, I did not see her, nor ask where she was. My Lord, I forgot to remark, that when we had been at Cassaday's about half an hour, we went to Mr. Langdale's, hearing his house was on fire; the prisoner lives in Union-court; he said his master's house would be burnt down, and he should lose all his tools; we went to Mr. Scott's, as his chest and some of his tools were there; Mr. Scott said there was no danger. We then went to Mr. Woollaston's, and asked if they wanted any help; they said they wanted all they could get; we staid and assisted them about half an hour; I believe it was near ten o'clock when we came away. We then went up to Mr. Cassaday's; we met Mr. Hayward near Mr. Woollaston's, we went with him to Long-lane, and bought a pig's head, or part of a pig's head; Mr. Hayward then went home without us, and we went immediately to Cassaday's, and staid till twelve o'clock.</p>
               <p>(On his cross examination, he said he frequently slept with the prisoner when he was out late; that he was constantly with the prisoner that night till twelve; that the prisoner was in no riot; that he (the witness) was a serjeant in the yellows; that he frequently went home with the prisoner, but could not particularly mention any other day when he had done so.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1558">
                  WILLIAM
                   GERRARD
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1558" type="surname" value="GERRARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1558" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1558" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I left my house about eight o'clock, and did not return till the next morning; I left 
               <persName id="t17800628-117-person1559">
                  William
                   Wildman
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1559" type="surname" value="Wildman"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1559" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1559" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and 
               <persName id="t17800628-117-person1560">
                  Thomas
                   Travers
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1560" type="surname" value="Travers"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1560" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1560" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             in the house.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1561">
                  WILLIAM
                   WILDMAN
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1561" type="surname" value="WILDMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1561" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1561" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I was in Mr. Gerrard's house when the mob came; I staid till it was all over; I never saw the prisoner in my life, to my knowledge, till I saw him afterwards in prison. Mr. Gerrard went out between seven and eight o'clock, and left the keys with Mr. Travers and me; we staid in the house till about ten o'clock; then we came out and locked the door, and staid at the door till the mob came; then a tall man came and knocked at the door, but not the prisoner, to my thinking he was a great deal older, he<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178006280274"></xptr> had a thin face, a black beard, a wig on, and he had a light drab frock: that man would have set the house on fire if it had not been for me and some of the neighbours; I did not observe any thing in his hand; he appeared cool, but very resolute to set the house on fire; I told them there was nobody in the house, and then two brewers servants broke two pannels of the door with a pump handle.</p>

               <p>Had either of those two, or the tall man, an ax? - I saw an ax, after it was done, in a drummer's hand; that was after they had got the goods down into Goswell-street, and set them on fire.</p>
               <p>"On his cross examination he said the</p>
               <p>"door was broke open about twenty minutes</p>
               <p>"after eleven o'clock; that when they had</p>
               <p>"broke the pannels, somebody said Mr.</p>
               <p>"Travers had the key; that they got it</p>
               <p>"from him, opened the door, and went in;</p>
               <p>"that he saw the drawers thrown out; that</p>
               <p>"there were several persons in the one-pair-of-stairs;</p>
               <p>"that one leaned out and said,</p>
               <p>"Huzza! all Popery! but he did not know</p>
               <p>"who it was; that he did not see any one</p>
               <p>"person there that he knew; that if the</p>
               <p>"prisoner had been there, and taken an active</p>
               <p>"part, he thought he must have seen</p>
               <p>"him."</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1562">
                  THOMAS
                   TRAVERS
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1562" type="surname" value="TRAVERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1562" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1562" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I live in Pear-tree-street; I had the key of the street-door and beer cellar left with me; Mr. Gerrard left the house about eight o'clock; we were moving some things out; we illuminated the house, and hung a blue flag out; Mr. Wildman and I came out, and were at the door when the mob came up; they knocked at the door two or three different times; there was a tallish man in a smock frock, which covered his clothes, and he had a wig; there were only two tall people, one in a drummer's dress, the other a shorter man; first they knocked at the door, then they began to break the pannels; I cannot say what with, but I afterwards found a pump-handle in the house.</p>
               <p>When they first came up did you observe any of them to have an ax? - I did not, indeed my flurry was very great; Mr. Couch informed me a person was taken up, and desired me to go with him to see him; I said I could not be certain to the person, I think the man that was there was something shorter than the prisoner, and had a wig; I do not think the prisoner is the man. When they had broke the pannels of the door I resigned the key to a Mr. Berry, and went away to a relation's of Mr. Gerrard's, to enquire for him; when I returned they were bringing out the goods to burn in Goswell-street.</p>
               <p>Was Berry so situated as to observe the people who were there? - He was at the door, and opened it to let them in.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1563">
                  WILLIAM
                   JONES
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1563" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1563" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1563" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am apprentice to Mr. Wood, a watch-maker, in Norman-street, Old-street; I went on Wednesday the 7th of June to see Mr. Gerrard's house, which I heard was pulled down; they were taking things to the fire; some men were beating on the bottom of a kettle for the mob to go with them; they said they would go to Golden-lane; there was a tall man and another with an ax, but neither of them were the prisoner; I did not see the prisoner there.</p>
               <p>Do you know the prisoner? - No, I never saw him to speak to him till I saw him in the bail-dock.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1564">
                  ABRAHAM
                   HUBBART
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1564" type="surname" value="HUBBART"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1564" type="given" value="ABRAHAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1564" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I belong to Mr. Wood, a watch-maker, in Norman-street; on Wednesday the 7th of June, at about eleven or twelve o'clock, I went to Mr. Gerrard's house, they were just pulling it down; I then went into Goswell-street to the fire of Mr. Gerrard's goods; I saw several people carry goods, but do not remember any person in particular; there was a tall man in a white coat and his own hair, but I think he was older than the prisoner.</p>
