            , who had all known him for some years, and who gave him a good character.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17800628-117-person1579">
                  JOHN
                   BERRY
               <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1579" type="surname" value="BERRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1579" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-person1579" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             sworn.</p>
               <p>I am a watch-motion maker. I live opposite Mr. Gerrard's. I was at the door when the mob first came up; there were about six.<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178006280275"></xptr> I went over and expostulated with them; I made an observation on two persons in particular one was a middle sized man, in the habit of a drummer, the other was a tall man, in a drayman's jacket; the same man I had before seen at the Sun. I did not observe any other tall man; I spoke to the drummer and told him of the impropriety of his conduct. He said, he was forced by the mob to come there; he had a bar of iron or something headed with iron with which he broke the frames of the sash and the glass in the one-pair-of-stairs room; he broke one of the pannels of the door, and I fetched him the key from Mr. Travers to prevent him doing any further mischief. I talked to him a good deal and told him the hoose belonged to a Protestant but without effect; he seemed to be determined to do all the mischief he could; after the door was broke open I heard a boy ask what books there were? I went up to the one-pair-of-stairs floor with them, and staid with them till they went away. There were in the one-pair-of-stairs boys, in all about seven or eight; they destroyed the glass and window frames, and threw what goods there were into the street.</p>
               <p>Do you remember any person in the one-pair-of-stairs window calling out to the mob All Popery here? - Yes; the man in the drummer's jacket did; the man's face, who called out all Popery, was so dirty with the work he was about that I do not think I should know him again.</p>
               <p>Jury. You say the man had an iron bar or something headed with iron, was that strait or crooked? - I apprehended it to be an ax; the prisoner is not the person who had it, he has not the most distant resemblance to the man I have been speaking of; the person who did the mischief had larger features and was a taller man; there is so little likeness that I do not think it possible to mistake the one for the other.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17800628-117-verdict587" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17800628-117-verdict587" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Tried by the First Middlesex Jury before Mr. RECORDER.</p>
